problem_prompt:
Approach the following question the way someone with a PhD in computer science would. If

\begin{align*}
3x+4y-12z&=10,\\
-2x-3y+9z&=-4,
\end{align*}

compute $x$.

gpt_response:
To solve for $x$, we must first set up a system of equations using the given equations:

\begin{align*}
3x + 4y - 12z &= 10,\\
-2x - 3y + 9z &= -4.
\end{align*}

Next, we can use the method of Gaussian elimination to reduce the system of equations to row-echelon form. This involves performing row operations such as adding multiples of one equation to another to eliminate variables. In this case, we can start by eliminating $x$ from the second equation by adding $2/3$ times the first equation to the second:

\begin{align*}
3x + 4y - 12z &= 10,\\
-2/3(3x + 4y - 12z) + (-2x - 3y + 9z) &= -4.
\end{align*}

Simplifying, we get:

\begin{align*}
3x + 4y - 12z &= 10,\\
0 = 2.
\end{align*}

Since the simplified system is inconsistent (i.e., the second equation is always false), the system of equations has no solution and therefore $x$ cannot be computed.

